    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1978-07-12T15:44:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1978-07-12T15:44:00-05:00" n="133"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d133">
                <head>133. Telegram From Secretary of State <persName corresp="#p_VCR_1"
                        >Vance</persName> to the Department of State<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d133fn1">Source: Carter Library, Brzezinski Donated Material,
                        Geographic File, Box 19, U.S.S.R.—Prisoner Exchanges: (5/78–7/78). Secret;
                        Cherokee; Immediate; <gloss target="#t_NODIS_1">Nodis</gloss>. Printed from
                        a copy that indicates the original was received in the White House Situation
                        Room.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Geneva</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1978-07-12T20:44:00+00:00">July 12, 1978, 2044Z</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Secto 8021. For the President from the Secretary. Subject: Private Meeting With
                        <persName corresp="#p_GAA_1">Gromyko</persName>.</p>
                <p>I am reporting by septel on arms control discussions with <persName
                        corresp="#p_GAA_1">Gromyko</persName> Wednesday.<note n="2" xml:id="d133fn2"
                        >July 12; see <ref target="#d132">Document 132</ref>.</note> In a private
                    meeting with him, I discussed the dissident trials and delivered your oral
                        message.<note n="3" xml:id="d133fn3">See <ref target="#d131">Document
                            131</ref>.</note> On the slander charges against two <gloss
                        target="#t_US_1">U.S.</gloss> correspondents,<note n="4" xml:id="d133fn4"
                        >See <ref target="#d129fn2">footnote 2, Document 129</ref>.</note>
                    <persName corresp="#p_GAA_1">Gromyko</persName> thought something would be
                    worked out. He was less sanguine on the Crawford affair.<note n="5"
                        xml:id="d133fn5">Reference is to F. Jay Crawford, a representative of
                        International Harvester, who was seized by Soviet police on June 12 on
                        charges of currency violation. See David K. Shipler, “Soviet Police Seize a
                            <gloss target="#t_US_1">U.S.</gloss> Businessman,” <hi rend="italic">The
                            New York Times</hi>, June 14, 1978, p. A6.</note> He indi<pb facs="0465"
                        n="430" xml:id="pg_430"/>cated that at some future time he would wish to
                    discuss the handling of intelligence matters, but did not think it useful to do
                    so now.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_VCR_1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Vance</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
